passages.text: Australia | Discretionary Retail
Equity ResearchAugust 29,2025

Result ticked all the boxes; NPAT & sales beat expectations, cashflow was strong & FY26 has started well with sales growing faster than both JB Aust & Good Guys in July. HVN is benefiting from improving conditions across the world as monetary policy eases & has historically been a good stock to own as the cycle turns, because it is exposed to more cyclical categories & has large operating leverage. Not as cheap as it was, but material discount to JBH. Buy.

**PBT (ex** **revals, post AASB16) of** **\(\)598.7m\(c.2\%\) ahead of consensus: Aust c. 5% above VA consensus, NZ c. 2% below, Asia broadly in line, Property (ex** **revals) c. 2% ahead. 14.5c final div (JEFe: 13.0c).**

**Strong cash flow: Op cash flow was** \(\)694m\(, up c. 1% on the pcp and implying cash realisation of 104% (JEFe: 84%). Company calculated cash conversion (ex AASB16) was 95% in FY25. Cash benefit from stronger sales was compounded by smaller financial accommodation to support franchisee inventory. Management suggested the current system inventory level was appropriate.

**Marketing expense continued to fall: Global marketing spend fell** \(\)15m\(to 4.0% of sales, down from 4.4% in FY24. Some spend was reallocated offshore & management suggested HVN has improved efficiency of marketing spend (fig 1).**

**Property now** \(\)3.64\(/share from** \(\)3.53\(/share in 1H: Property now valued at** \(\)4.5b\((slightly\)>50% of market cap), up 7% (\)\\(298m\)\text {YoY. Property reval increment made up }\)\\(154m\) of the increase, with remainder from investment. Cap rate on top 20 properties slightly higher & remains very conservative relative to listed REITs (fig 2-3).

**Balance sheet very conservative: We consider HVN's financial leverage at 2.1x to be very** conservative, given substantial property. Net debt (ex leases) is \(\)659m\(, representing LVR of only 15% on the property. 30-40% would be reasonable, and that is without allowing for cash flows from the retail business (fig 4).**

**HVN has more operating leverage than JBH: Over past 6 years, HVN's average op leverage** has been c. 4.8x. i.e. its change in EBIT is c. 4.8x its change in sales. This compares to JB HiFi Aust, which has much lower op leverage (c. 1.5x). We attribute this to HVN's higher GM/ higher CODB model & JBH's tighter cost control. While higher leverage doesn't make HVN a better business, it does mean it should deliver better growth in a favourable cycle.

We believe HVN is fundamentally a good business. It is run for the long term and management has little concern about short- term volatility, but the franchise structure incentivises a strong sales culture.

HVN is seeing early benefits from improving demand, translating to operating leverage & margin expansion in Australia. Stock trades at material discount to JBH and NCK, and while HVN doesn't have the same execution track record, it has a history of delivering strong results when the cycle turns, and has material property backing. We see long- term upside from the UK & Asia expansion, noting the Group has a reasonable track record of developing new markets.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View
- Improving demand drives operating leverage & margin expansion.- Macro conditions improve in Australia- International expansion in the UK & Asia delivers in the long-term.- Price Target at \(7.80
- Macro pressures subside faster than expected bolstered by further interest rate cuts.- Sales growth accelerates and margins recover faster.- Upside case price target \(8.50\)
- Cycle not as favorable as hoped & offshore expansions are problematic- Downside case price target \(6.00\)
Top Material Issue(s): 1) Corporate governance. 2) Environmental impact: reduce emissions, packaging, energy consumption and waste. 3) Sustainable supply chain management.

Company Target(s): 1) Achieving gender diversity in the composition of the Board of not less than \(30\%\) of its directors of each gender within a specified period. 2) Minimise waste by offering E- waste recycling across all franchised complexes.

Qs to Mgmt: 1) Is there a plan to have an independent majority on the Board going forward? 2) What is the investment criteria and approval process regarding investments in non- core businesses? 3) What capex investment is required to achieve your sustainability goals and what are the financial returns, particularly in relation to solar installations across Australian complexes?
Link to Sector Framework
- Economic indicators (house prices, unemployment etc).- ABS retail trade.

The Group's freehold property portfolio is now valued at \(\) 4.53b\(\) (slightly \(>50\%\) of market cap or c. \(\) 3.64\(/share), up 7.0\% (\) 298m) from the pcp. Net property revaluation increments made up \(\) 154m\(of the increase, with the remainder from investments. Weighted avg cap rate on top 20 properties expanded 2bps to 6.19\%\) and properties appear to be conservatively valued relative to peers. Property has historically provided a share price floor, but it is less relevant with the share price well above property value.

Operating cash flow was \(694.3m\) up c. \(1\%\) on the pc and implying cash realisation of \(104\%\) (JEFE \(84\%\) ). Company- calculated cash conversion (excluding interest, tax, AASB16 adjustment, and net property revals) indicates cash conversion of \(95.1\%\) in FY25, lower than \(100\%\) in FY25. Higher net receipts from franchisees in 2H25 was driven by higher sales and lower funding requests to fund inventory purchases.

Inventory across the Australian and International system has largely normalised close to pre- COVID levels after a period of elevated working capital. Receivables from franchisees (proxy for inventory) was c. \(12.2\%\) sales in 2H25, down from c. \(13.1\%\) in the pcp but higher than c. \(11\%\) pre- COVID. Company inventory is c. \(21\%\) retail sales (ex Australia), above pre- COVID levels of c. \(18\%\) which we attribute to new store openings yet to mature.

Total global marketing expenses in the 8 countries as a percentage of total system sales was \(4.0\%\) in FY25, down from \(4.4\%\) in the ppc. This is above pandemic lows but remains below pre- COVID levels of \(>5\%\) . Marketing spend in Australian franchisees was c. \(4.9\%\) (down c. \(\) 20m\(YoY) and remains efficient according to the company. Some marketing spend was reallocated to the international system but marketing as a\) \%\(of sales in the International System is lower than Australia, which management attributed to the nature of the markets it operates in.

As outlined in the chart below, leverage has steadily declined after peaking in 2H24 and is now c. \(2.1x\) . This is higher than historical levels, but the comparison is not apples- to- apples, given we capitalise leases from FY20. We are not worried, given our view that gearing is still low, taking into account the property portfolio. Net debt (ex leases) is only \(\) 659m\(. This represents only\)15\%\(of the property portfolio. 30 - 40\%\) would be reasonable, and that is without allowing for the cash flows from the retail business.

Harvey Norman operates a retail, franchise and property business. Its Australian operations are conducted through a franchise structure, while its offshore business is through a traditional retail model. Its retail model operates in New Zealand, Singapore & Malaysia, Slovenia & Croatia, Ireland and Northern Ireland. Its property portfolio is significant (c. A\\$4.1bn). It also operates the Space, Domayne and Joyce Mayne brands.

Our primary valuation methodology is a DCF model, which we believe most appropriately captures through- the- cycle earnings and capex associated with the offshore expansion. We use assumptions consistent with our broader Consumer coverage. Risks: House prices, consumer confidence, and offshore execution.

Buy - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of \(15\%\) or more within a 12- month period. Hold - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of plus \(15\%\) or minus \(10\%\) within a 12- month period. Underperform - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of minus \(10\%\) or less within a 12- month period. The expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) for Buy rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) is \(20\%\) or more within a 12- month period as these companies are typically more volatile than the overall stock market. For Hold rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is plus or minus \(20\%\) within a 12- month period. For Underperform rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is minus \(20\%\) or less within a 12- month period.
NR - The investment rating and price target have been temporarily suspended. Such suspensions are in compliance with applicable regulations and/or Jefferies policies.
CS - Coverage Suspended. Jefferies has suspended coverage of this company.
NC - Not covered. Jefferies does not cover this company.

Restricted - Describes issuers where, in conjunction with Jefferies engagement in certain transactions, company policy or applicable securities regulations prohibit certain types of communications, including investment recommendations.
Monitor - Describes securities whose company fundamentals and financials are being monitored, and for which no financial projections or opinions on the investment merits of the company are provided.

Jefferies' methodology for assigning ratings may include the following: market capitalization, maturity, growth/value, volatility and expected total return over the next 12 months. The price targets are based on several methodologies, which may include, but are not restricted to, analyses of market risk, growth rate, revenue stream, discounted cash flow (DCF), EBITDA, EPS, cash flow (CF), free cash flow (FCF), EV/EBITDA, P/E, PE/growth, P/CF, P/FCF, premium (discount)/average group EV/EBITDA, premium (discount)/average group P/E, sum of the parts, net asset value, dividend returns, and return on equity (ROE) over the next 12 months.

Jefferies Franchise Picks include stock selections from among the best stock ideas from our equity analysts over a 12 month period. Stock selection is based on fundamental analysis and may take into account other factors such as analyst conviction, differentiated analysis, a favorable risk/reward ratio and investment themes that Jefferies analysts are recommending. Jefferies Franchise Picks will include only Buy rated stocks and the number can vary depending on analyst recommendations for inclusion. Stocks will be added as new opportunities arise and removed when the reason for inclusion changes, the stock has met its desired return, if it is no longer rated Buy and/or if it triggers a stop loss.
